{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f30ec792-1196-458f-ac42-48f8f89be549","content":"\n\nHere's how to connect your C# MCP server to the **MCP Inspector**:\n\n### 1. Run the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published binary:\n\n- **Command:** `/path/to/YourServer`\n\n### 3. Click **Connect**\n\nThe Inspector will spawn your process, communicate over stdin/stdout, and show you:\n\n- Available **tools**, **resources**, and **prompts**\n- A panel to invoke tools with custom inputs\n- Raw JSON-RPC message logs for debugging\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Don't write to stdout** in your server for anything other than MCP JSON-RPC messages — use `stderr` for logging, or the Inspector won't parse responses correctly.\n- If your server needs environment variables, set them in the **Environment Variables** section of the Inspector UI.\n- Use the **raw message log** at the bottom to diagnose serialization or protocol issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4294d9a9-39bc-4200-a865-1df578c86c7f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore their codebase. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":359},"id":"b417409d-04d5-4b44-bbbf-ed4b310271f5","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:22.017Z","parentId":"2391dd33-a782-44e0-9f06-6a2a07bbaf79"}
